Some Background on Lassa Fever in Sierra Leone
----------------------------------------------
[The following information relating to the ProMED-mail post "Lassa fever -
Sierra Leone (Kenema) 20040420.1096" has been extracted from the GIDEON
database by Dr. Steve Berger. - Mod.CP]
Lassa fever is most common in the eastern region; one to 4 _Mastomys_
[small, mouse-life African rodents] are found in every household in this
area, of which 1-20 percent are infected with Lassa virus. In some areas of
eastern Sierra Leone, the disease accounts for 30 percent of medical death
in-hospital, 30 percent of deafness and 70 percent of spontaneous abortion.
8-52 percent of the population are seropositive.
Notable outbreaks:
------------------
1970 to 1972 - 63 cases were reported in Panguma-Tongo region (Eastern
Province) during October 1970 to October 1972.
1995 - An outbreak (167 cases, 60 fatal) was reported in Kenema District --
most patients were adolescent females.
1996 - 799 cases (148 fatal) were reported, including 99 cases (13 fatal)
from Kenema District during November and December.
1997 - 353 (43 fatal) cases were reported during January to April 1997.
2003 - An outbreak of suspected Lassa fever (80 cases, 8 fatal) was
reported in the central region, with several cases reported in refugee camps.
2004 - An outbreak was reported in Kenema district.
Exported cases:
--------------
1976 - A Peace Corps worker returned to the United States from Sierra Leone
with Lassa fever.
1987 - An Israeli national acquired Lassa fever in Sierra Leone, and
survived under treatment in Israel.
2000 - A British national acquired Lassa fever in Sierra Leone, and died
while under treatment in England.
2000 - A Dutch national acquired Lassa fever in Sierra Leone, and died
while under treatment in the Netherlands.
2003 - A British national acquired Lassa fever in Sierra Leone, and was
treated successfully in the U.K.
--
Steve Berger
Geographic Medicine
